{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780742168638,"sessionID":"ses_16384c53affe2f7jn8iVrlwqWM","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_02_gOxbyjtBgoqujSBMoQSX7187","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"include":"*.json","pattern":"hook.*timeout|timeout.*hook|SKILL_ADVISOR|session_bootstrap|memory_context","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode"},"output":"Found 280 matches (showing first 100)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/risk-resolution/deep-research-config.json:\n  Line 2:   \"topic\": \"Run 3 — RISK RESOLUTION before implementation of the spec-memory dual-stack CLI. PREMISE (settled, do not relitigate): run-1 GO verdict in ../research.md and the run-2 CLI design in ../cli-backend/lineages/gpt/research.md — READ BOTH as input. EXCLUSION: do not read anything under this run's sibling lineages directory (research/risk-resolution/lineages/ other than your own lane folder); findings derived from a sibling lane are void. MISSION: investigate EVERY risk and unknown below until each is classified RESOLVED (with file:line or measured evidence), MITIGATED (named design delta the implementation packet must absorb), ACCEPTED (explicit rationale), or DEFERRED (named blocker) — and ADD any newly discovered risks/unknowns as new key questions which must also reach a terminal classification. The loop is done only when every question is classified; read-only timing measurements via bash are allowed, file mutation is not. The seed register: RQ1 daemon-bypass enforcement — can the public CLI provably never open the database directly; inventory every admin direct-DB path; the unix-socket trust model (which local processes can connect; socket file permissions). RQ2 schema-drift mechanics — do all 37 tool arg shapes (nested objects, arrays, unions) round-trip via argv flags plus a --json escape hatch; is codegen from TOOL_DEFINITIONS feasible for every tool; enumerate the tools whose schemas do not map cleanly to flags. RQ3 lease/spawn races — CLI auto-spawn while an MCP session owns the daemon; two CLIs spawning simultaneously; lifetime and ownership of a CLI-spawned daemon when no MCP session exists (who reaps it, idle timeout, orphan risk — six orphaned mk-skill-advisor launchers were observed on this host today as a cautionary precedent). RQ4 retryable taxonomy — the complete error-to-exit-75 map: -32001, cold-start exhaustion, lease contention, SQLITE_BUSY; which daemon errors are genuinely retryable versus terminal (exit 69). RQ5 hook latency budget — ...\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/028-memory-mcp-cli-feasibility/research/deep-research-config.json:\n  Line 2:   \"topic\": \"Can the system-spec-kit memory MCP (mk-spec-memory, 37 tools) be replaced by a CLI with ZERO feature loss? Evaluate three architectures — (a) pure per-invocation CLI, (b) CLI front-end over the existing daemon/IPC socket (kill only the MCP protocol layer), (c) hybrid CLI that auto-spawns the daemon on demand — scoring each against the zero-feature-loss bar across 5 key questions: KQ1 parity matrix for all 37 tools with a CLI equivalent per tool (prior art: generate-context.js already does memory_save; ~11 maintenance CLIs under scripts/dist/memory/); KQ2 daemon-dependency audit (warm embedder, file-watcher reindex, async retry queue/enrichment, RSS watchdog, single-writer serialization, warm session briefs — what dies per architecture); KQ3 MCP-only affordances and replacements (tool-schema auto-discovery, runtime permissioning, Zod boundary validation, -32001 retryable plus session-proxy replay semantics); KQ4 integration-surface migration (runtime hooks for Claude/OpenCode/Codex/Copilot calling session_bootstrap and memory_context, agents allowed-tools, /doctor flows, deep-loop allowed-tools); KQ5 comparison of a/b/c with effort estimates, risk register, go/no-go recommendation. Evidence: a mid-session MCP disconnect left Claude Code unable to reconnect while a CLI re-bridges per call; the launcher/IPC layer already speaks JSON-RPC over daemon-ipc.sock.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/005-live-rescope-coco-purge/findings-registry.json:\n  Line 2963:       \"text\": \"`/spec_kit:resume` already gives the ordering model: prefer fresh `handover.md`, then `memory_context` resume mode, crash breadcrumbs, anchored search, recent-candidate discovery, and only then user confirmation; a 027 context bundle should reuse that sequence before adding resource-map and graph checks. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md:280-296]\",\n\n  Line 2993:       \"text\": \"A context bundle should start with Spec Kit memory/resume, not code search: `memory_context` is documented as the L1 entry point for context retrieval, supports resume mode, and explicitly routes code search to Code Graph plus Grep instead of pretending memory is code search. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/tool-schemas.ts:40-44]\",\n\n  Line 3299:       \"text\": \"Prior 027 research already split the bundled Coco extras from the memory curator: Coco few-shot exemplars belong in 028, while LLM-curated `memory_context` is a 027 memory-backend concern that attaches `data.curatedContext` and does not touch coco-index ranking paths. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/iterations/iteration-039.md:53-59]\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/023-hybrid-rag-fusion-refinement/010-search-retrieval-quality-fixes/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 199:     \"causal_summary\": \"This is **Phase 10** of the ESM Module Compliance specification. It addresses six retrieval quality issues discovered during root-cause analysis of `memory_context` returning 0 results for \\\"semantic search\\\" — a query that should match 20+ memories.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/003-memory-and-causal-runtime/001-continuity-memory-runtime/005-memory-search-runtime-bugs/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 18:       \"memory_context truncation drops results\",\n\n  Line 200:     \"causal_summary\": \"A live `/memory:search` session against the indexed-continuity runtime exposed contract violations and degraded UX across the retrieval, output rendering, and causal-graph subcommands. The empty-arguments gate fired correctly, but every downstream stage produced at least one observable defect: the intent classifier emitted `fix_bug` (confidence 0.098) for the query \\\"Semantic Search\\\" despite the spec mandating `understand` as the no-keyword-match fallback; the `memory_context` wrapper reported `truncated=true` and zero `results` while consuming only 2% of its 3000-3500 token budget; the assistant rendering used the explicitly-forbidden phrase \\\"Auto-triggered memories\\\"; `causal-stats` returned three of six valid relation types and labeled itself `health: \\\"healthy\\\"` while reporting `meetsTarget: false`. The root spec at `.opencode/commands/memory/search.md` documents the intended behavior, but the runtime drifts from it on multiple axes.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/006-research/004-fix-deep-research-findings/003-fix-skill-advisor-quality/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 198:     \"causal_summary\": \"Eight advisor-quality findings sit across the skill-advisor surface. (B1-01) The Codex hook timeout fallback emits a bespoke advisor brief that bypasses the shared `renderAdvisorBrief()` formatter, so a future format change drifts between runtimes. (B1-02) The OpenCode bridge surfaces `Advisor: disabled by SPECKIT_SKILL_ADVISOR_HOOK_DISABLED.` to the model when the disabled flag is set, while every other runtime fails open silently — disabled-state visibility is not aligned. (B1-03) The OpenCode bridge carries a dead `renderNativeBrief()` alternate renderer that is unreferenced and can drift out of sync with the shared formatter. (C2-01) Graph-causal conflict evidence (negative `EDGE_MULTIPLIER` for `conflicts_with`) is filtered out at lane emit (`value.score > 0`), so conflict signals never reach fusion. (C2-02) The SQLite projection assigns `derivedKeywords = derivedTriggers` (same value), duplicating the same evidence into two lane inputs. (C2-03) The fusion task-intent confidence floor (0.75) lets token-stuffed prompts pass for many unrelated skills as soon as ANY direct/normalized score scrap clears the threshold — there is no dispersion guard. (C2-04) `isAmbiguousTopTwo` compares only the top two `confidence` values, ignoring the larger ranking-score signal and any third-or-deeper tied candidates. (C3-01) Fixture row 26 expects `sk-code-review` for `\\\"review and update this\\\"`, but the prompt is a write/edit request — the fixture encodes a review-only routing that conflicts with the write-verb signal.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/005-stress-test/003-fix-mcp-runtime-stress-findings/008-mcp-daemon-rebuild-protocol/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 196:     \"causal_summary\": \"The 005 packet implementation summary claimed Cluster 1-3 P0 fixes landed. The post-remediation verification (recorded in 005/spec.md §7) showed Probes A and B regressing the original defect: live `memory_context({input:\\\"Semantic Search\\\"})` still emitted `meta.intent.type:\\\"fix_bug\\\"` (0.098) and `data.content[0].text:{count:0,results:[]}`. 007/Q1 (Iteration 001) ruled out a missing dist rebuild — `dist/` markers were present and timestamps were newer than source. The remaining cause was that the MCP-owning client/runtime had not been restarted; the running daemon child process continued using the old code. This is the canonical \\\"phantom fix\\\" failure mode and it is structural, not implementation-specific.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/005-stress-test/003-fix-mcp-runtime-stress-findings/003-memory-context-truncation-telemetry-contract/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 19:       \"memory_context payload count invariant\",\n\n  Line 205:     \"causal_summary\": \"The 005 post-remediation verification (2026-04-26 18:49) showed that the Cluster 1 truncation fix is NOT live in the daemon: `memory_context({input:\\\"Semantic Search\\\"})` still returns `meta.tokenBudgetEnforcement.{enforced:true, truncated:true, returnedResultCount:3, originalResultCount:5}` while `actualTokens=65 / budgetTokens=3500` (1.9% utilization) and `data.content[0].text` still contains `{\\\"count\\\":0,\\\"results\\\":[]}`. The 007 research isolated the root cause as soft contracts: `actualTokens` is reported AFTER fallback (post-enforcement size), there is no `preEnforcementTokens` to distinguish overflow from returned size, and the wrapper has no payload/count invariant assertion that the metadata's `returnedResultCount` matches the actual `JSON.parse(content[0].text).data.results.length`.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/005-stress-test/003-fix-mcp-runtime-stress-findings/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 210:     \"causal_summary\": \"The MCP runtime serves four high-traffic surfaces — `memory_context`, `memory_search`, `code_graph_query`, `memory_causal_stats` — that AI assistants depend on for retrieval and grounding. Under realistic CLI load these surfaces had subtle contract gaps: token-budget envelopes that under-reported truncation, code-graph blocked reads with no machine-readable fallback hint, causal-graph relation balance with no per-window cap or skew detection, intent telemetry that could not be aggregated across runtimes, and a `memory_search` weak-quality path that lacked a server-side refusal contract. The combined effect was ungrounded responses, runtime hallucinations, and silent CLI thrashing that the operator could not trace.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/descriptions.json:\n  Line 7116:       \"description\": \"Feature Specification: memory_context truncation contract + token telemetry\",\n\n  Line 7437:       \"description\": \"Research Charter: memory_context Structural Channel Routing\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/013-comprehensive-audit-remediation/scratch/verified-backlog.json:\n  Line 160:           \"title\": \"memory_search does not validate caller sessionId via resolveTrustedSession like memory_context/memory_match_triggers do\",\n\n  Line 164:           \"fix\": \"Mirror the memory-triggers.ts:226-246 pattern. After destructuring (line 664) and before sessionId is first consumed for dedup/boost, when sessionId is provided, call sessionManager.resolveTrustedSession(sessionId, { tenantId, userId, agentId }); if trustedSession.error, return createMCPErrorResponse({ tool: 'memory_search', code: 'E_SESSION_SCOPE', error: trustedSession.error, recovery: { hint: 'Omit sessionId to start a new server-generated session, or reuse the effectiveSessionId returned by memory_context.' } }); otherwise replace the local sessionId with trustedSession.effectiveSessionId so all downstream dedup/boost/progressiveScopeKey use the validated id. Keep behavior identical when sessionId is omitted (current callers that omit it are unaffected). sessionManager is already imported (memory-search.ts:10).\",\n\n  Line 174:           \"title\": \"No-session callers get collapsed onto one shared process-wide session (memory_context replaces freshly-minted per-call session id with a process-wide id)\",\n\n  Line 306:           \"evidence\": \"CONFIRMED contradiction. context-server.ts:953 tells non-hook runtimes: 'If \\\"stale\\\": mcp__mk_code_index__code_graph_query still works, but a session_bootstrap refresh is recommended', and 966-967 only surfaces the query routing rule when freshness is 'fresh' or 'stale'. But query.ts shouldBlockReadPath (866-875) returns true whenever `readiness.freshness !== 'fresh'` (explicitly a 'false-safe contract' that refuses to answer on a stale graph — comment 866-873), and the read handler at 1244 returns `status:'blocked'` / `code_graph_not_ready` for that case. So on a stale graph code_graph_query does NOT work — it blocks. The guidance is wrong.\",\n\n  Line 307:           \"fix\": \"Correct the guidance text in context-server.ts:953 to match the handler's false-safe contract: a stale graph BLOCKS reads and requires a refresh (session_bootstrap, or code_graph_scan) before code_graph_query returns results — e.g. 'If \\\"stale\\\": code_graph_query will block (code_graph_not_ready) until you run session_bootstrap to refresh; run it first.' Also reconcile the routing-rule gate at 966-967 so the 'Structural queries → code_graph_query' rule is only emitted for 'fresh' (stale should route to a refresh action, not a direct query). This is a docs/guidance-string fix in code, not a behavior change to the handler (the handler's fail-closed block is correct and should stay).\",\n\n  Line 618:           \"title\": \"Playbook/catalog examples use stale MCP call shapes (session_bootstrap input/includeGraphStatus; memory_ingest_start dryRun)\",\n\n  Line 621:           \"evidence\": \"Scenario 032 line 37: 'session_bootstrap({ input: \\\"resume mk-spec-memory playbook audit\\\", includeGraphStatus: true })'. Current tool-schemas.ts session_bootstrap inputSchema (lines 651-660) accepts only 'specFolder' (optional string). Parameters 'input' and 'includeGraphStatus' do not exist in the schema. Catalog 253 line 28: 'memory_ingest_start(paths, dryRun)'. Current tool-schemas.ts memory_ingest_start inputSchema (lines 531-551) accepts 'paths' (array, required) and 'specFolder' (optional string). Parameter 'dryRun' does not exist.\",\n\n  Line 622:           \"fix\": \"In 032-session-bootstrap-reader-ready-context.md line 37, replace the stale call shape with the current schema: 'session_bootstrap({})' or 'session_bootstrap({ specFolder: \\\"<optional-folder>\\\" })'. In 253-governed-ingest-cancel-lifecycle.md line 28, replace 'memory_ingest_start(paths, dryRun)' with 'memory_ingest_start({ paths: [...] })' (dryRun removed, specFolder is the optional second param).\",\n\n  Line 627:           \"verification\": \"After fix: grep the two files for 'includeGraphStatus' and 'dryRun' (in the ingest context) should return 0 hits. The canonical call shapes come from mcp_server/tool-schemas.ts session_bootstrap (line 651) and memoryIngestStart (line 531).\",\n\n  Line 628:           \"risk\": \"The cluster-D note says the canonical call shapes come from cluster D. Coordinate: confirm no cluster D fix changes the session_bootstrap or memory_ingest_start schemas before applying doc fixes here.\"\n\n  Line 631:       \"notes\": \"All 10 findings verified against current working tree. TOOL_DEFINITIONS.length confirmed at 37 by direct Python parse of the array. Scenario file count confirmed at 384 by running the playbook's own glob logic. All 5 broken catalog paths in F4 confirmed with ls. Phase-style labels '[Phase 007]' and 'Phase 027' confirmed present in mcp_server/tool-schemas.ts:349 and mcp_server/context-server.ts:950. The verify_alignment_drift.py script is at sk-code/assets/scripts/ not sk-code/scripts/. session_bootstrap schema has only specFolder; memory_ingest_start schema has paths+specFolder, no dryRun. No findings are ALREADY_FIXED or MISREPORTED. F7 code fix (removing the phase labels) is owned by cluster A; this cluster owns only the catalog claim accuracy.\"\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/012-comprehensive-deep-review-audit/002-mcp-retrieval-causal/review/lineages/codex-1/deep-review-findings-registry.json:\n  Line 12:       \"title\": \"memory_context collapses all no-session callers onto one process-scoped session\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/012-comprehensive-deep-review-audit/002-mcp-retrieval-causal/review/lineages/codex-3/deep-review-findings-registry.json:\n  Line 10:       \"title\": \"memory_context omitted-session calls reuse a process-wide fallback\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/012-comprehensive-deep-review-audit/003-mcp-session-index-schema/review/lineages/codex-4/deep-review-findings-registry.json:\n  Line 64:       \"summary\": \"The playbook calls session_bootstrap with input/includeGraphStatus and the catalog advertises memory_ingest_start(paths, dryRun), but live schemas accept only the current parameter sets.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/012-comprehensive-deep-review-audit/003-mcp-session-index-schema/review/deep-review-findings-registry.json:\n  Line 75:       \"summary\": \"The playbook calls session_bootstrap with input/includeGraphStatus and the catalog advertises memory_ingest_start(paths, dryRun), but live schemas accept only the current parameter sets.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/022-hybrid-rag-fusion/014-agents-md-alignment/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 194:     \"causal_summary\": \"The three AGENTS.md governance framework files reference outdated Quick Reference workflow tables that show 5 memory commands instead of the current 4-command memory surface. The `/memory:learn` constitutional memory row only documents the `[rule]` creation subcommand, missing `list`, `edit`, `remove`, and `budget`. The `/memory:manage` database maintenance row is missing the `ingest` subcommand and the nested `/memory:manage shared` shared-memory lifecycle route. The retrieval row still points at the retired analyze command name instead of `/memory:search`. Additionally, the FS-Enterprises variant has a stale Research/exploration row missing the `memory_context()` unified alternative.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/006-operator-tooling/001-hook-parity/001-fix-runtime-hook-parity-findings/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 239:     \"causal_summary\": \"This phase closes hook parity defects discovered on 2026-04-21 across the OpenCode plugin bridge, Codex advisor hooks, Copilot startup routing, Codex PreToolUse safety, and runtime documentation. The implementation keeps each runtime on its real capability surface: OpenCode injects through the plugin bridge, Codex uses prompt/pre-tool hooks plus `session_bootstrap` for startup recovery, and Copilot starts through the repo-local wrapper.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/003-memory-and-causal-runtime/003-embedder-testing-and-architecture/006-mcp-launcher-concurrency/008-launcher-race-window-and-debug-log-hygiene/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 16:       \"MK_SKILL_ADVISOR_DEBUG\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/002-spec-kit-internals/002-skill-advisor/006-playbook-run-and-remediation/001-preconditions-and-build/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 199:     \"causal_summary\": \"The playbook's §2 global preconditions require a current MCP server build, an unset `SPECKIT_SKILL_ADVISOR_HOOK_DISABLED` flag, and evidence workspaces before any scenario can run. The CLI-delegated waves additionally require `cli-devin` and `cli-opencode` to be installed and authenticated. None of this had been confirmed for the current session.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/006-research/004-fix-deep-research-findings/009-fix-test-reliability/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 203:     \"causal_summary\": \"Six tests in the stress-test and unit-test surface have reliability defects that make them brittle on non-developer machines, in CI, or under repeated runs. One test hard-codes the original developer's local checkout path. One asserts absolute latency budgets that can fail on slower hardware. One uses real-timer sleeps with elapsed-time assertions, slowing the suite and producing flakes. Two tests mutate process env vars (`SPECKIT_SKILL_ADVISOR_PLUGIN_DISABLED`, `SPECKIT_MMR`) without restoration, leaking state across the run. One test uses a repo-local temp fixture root that collides between parallel runs and survives crashes.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/005-stress-test/003-fix-mcp-runtime-stress-findings/027-memory-context-structural-channel-research/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 17:       \"memory_context structural routing\",\n\n  Line 20:       \"memory_context structural routing plan\",\n\n  Line 22:       \"memory_context structural routing tasks\",\n\n  Line 24:       \"memory_context structural routing checklist\",\n\n  Line 26:       \"memory_context structural routing implementation summary\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/005-stress-test/003-fix-mcp-runtime-stress-findings/001-search-intelligence-stress-playbook/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 204:     \"causal_summary\": \"The system-spec-kit \\\"Search / Query / Intelligence\\\" surfaces (memory_search, memory_context, code_graph_query, advisor_recommend, intent classifier, etc.) have grown organically across 26+ optimization packets. Sibling packet `005-memory-search-runtime-bugs` catalogs 17 defects observed in a single live session. We need a reproducible, cross-AI stress-test that quantifies how well the search intelligence performs under realistic prompt variation — not just bug-hunt, but ongoing quality regression.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/z_future/code-graph-and-cocoindex/009-cocoindex-memory-port-research/research/findings-registry.json:\n  Line 60:       \"text\": \"**K2.3**: After `spec_kit_memory → mk_memory`, full tool names remain redundant (`mcp__mk_memory__memory_context`). Should tools also drop `memory_*`? Or shorten server to bare `mk`?\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/005-stress-test/003-fix-mcp-runtime-stress-findings/027-memory-context-structural-channel-research/description.json:\n  Line 3:   \"description\": \"Research Charter: memory_context Structural Channel Routing\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/000-release-and-program-cleanup/005-stress-test/003-fix-mcp-runtime-stress-findings/003-memory-context-truncation-telemetry-contract/description.json:\n  Line 3:   \"description\": \"Feature Specification: memory_context truncation contract + token telemetry\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/003-memory-and-causal-runtime/001-continuity-memory-runtime/005-memory-search-runtime-bugs/description.json:\n  Line 6:     \"memory_context truncation drops results\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/006-operator-tooling/003-install-scripts-doctor-realignment/001-deep-research-install-scripts-doctor/research/findings-registry.json:\n  Line 291:       \"text\": \"**[P3 / HISTORICAL]** `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/INSTALL_GUIDE.md:1197` — ``| v1.7.x | 2026-02-20 | Cross-encoder reranking enabled by default. Co-activation score boost fix. Query expansion on deep mode. Evidence gap warnings. MMR reranking with intent-mapped lambda. Phase system support (recursive validation, phase detection scoring). Feature flag updates. `memory_context` tokenUsage parameter. 28-tool surface area. |``.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/006-operator-tooling/001-hook-parity/003-codex-native-startup-advisor-hooks/research/deep-research-config.json:\n  Line 2:   \"topic\": \"Codex CLI hook parity: nail down the exact stdin/stdout/exit-code/timeout/ordering contract for ~/.codex/hooks.json so we can port the Claude UserPromptSubmit + SessionStart hooks without shipping against assumptions.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/004-code-graph/005-resilience-and-advisor/001-code-graph-advisor-refinement/research/001-code-graph-advisor-refinement-roadmap/findings-registry.json:\n  Line 1627:       \"text\": \"This looks like the user hand-authored a Codex-style entry with `\\\"type\\\":\\\"command\\\"` + `\\\"bash\\\":\\\"...\\\"` at the top, then wrapped a Claude-native entry with `{command,timeout}` inside a `hooks:[...]` array. Whether Claude Code executes the top or the nested entry depends on Claude's hook schema interpreter. At least one of these paths runs the WRONG runtime's adapter.\",\n\n  Line 3098:       \"id\": \"finding-11-7-optional-assert-timeouts-match-expected-values-3s-for-fast-hooks-10s-async-true-\",\n\n  Line 3099:       \"text\": \"Optional: assert timeouts match expected values (3s for fast hooks, 10s + `async: true` for `Stop`).\",\n\n  Line 4488:       \"text\": \"MODIFY: 1 entry point to read `SKILL_ADVISOR_PROMOTION_MODE` env var\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/003-memory-and-causal-runtime/003-embedder-testing-and-architecture/002-spec-memory-stack/022-hardcoded-default-remediation-arc/004a-skill-advisor-compat-contract-consolidation/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 43:       {\"name\": \"SKILL_ADVISOR_COMPAT_CONTRACT\", \"kind\": \"const\", \"path\": \".opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/compat/contract.ts\", \"source\": \"derived\"}\n\n  Line 45:     \"causal_summary\": \"Wave 1 of phase 004. 5 production files in skill-advisor lib wired to import confidence + uncertainty thresholds from SKILL_ADVISOR_COMPAT_CONTRACT.defaults. Closes 14 P0 audit findings. Waves 2-4 deferred to 004b after pre-execution investigation revealed council's file paths didn't match actual structure.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-